  "articleSummary": "The article critiques the flawed use of fixed-priority dropdowns (e.g., Jira's `P1-P4`) in software teams, arguing they lead to \"priority inflation\" as organizations endlessly add levels like `P00` to handle new urgent tasks. It frames this as a failure to model the fluid, context-dependent nature of real-world priorities, which shift with stakeholder needs, market changes, and resource constraints. The author advocates for unbounded numerical priorities or multidimensional scoring systems (e.g., MoSCoW method) to better capture dynamic priorities, while cautioning against the chaos of unmanaged \"z-index wars\" in similar systems. The tone is analytical and critical, blending technical examples (Jira, `z-index`) with metaphors like \"Engineering Theater\" and \"Bizzaro Trophy Room\" to highlight the absurdity of bloated backlogs. Targeted at software teams and project managers, it urges a shift from rigid labels to disciplined, adaptive prioritization",
